  "texts": [
    "Using that the functions | log(1 -w)| and | log(1 + w)| belong to L q ′ (I) for any q ′ ∈ [1, +∞), we apply Hölder's inequality with conjugate exponents q and q ′ = q q-1, and infer the upper bounds∫ I log(1 -w)h(t, w)dw ≤ ∥log(1 -w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I)), ∫ I log(1 + w)h(t, w)dw ≤ ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I)),which allow to finally control T 2 (t) asT 2 (t) ≤ η (1 + ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I))) e -τ t.(52)Note that obviously ∥log(1 -w)∥ L q ′ (I) = ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) and we have once again renamed η to account for all successive upper bounds of the constants.",
    "Combining estimates (51) and (52), we finally deduce thatd dt H(h|h eq)(t) ≤ -I H (h|h eq)(t) + η (1 + ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I))) e -τ t.(53)We proceed by introducing the Hellinger distanceD(h|h eq)(t) = ( ∫ I ( √ h(t, w) - √ h eq (t, w)) 2 dw)1 2, between h(t, w) and h eq (t, w), for which holds the fundamental relationD 2 (h|h eq)(t) ≤ 1 2 I H (h|h eq)(t),(54)proven in [19].",
    "Moreover, its temporal evolution readsd dt D 2 (h|h eq)(t) = ∫ I ⎛ ⎜ ⎝ 1 - h eq (t, w) h(t, w) ⎞ ⎟ ⎠ ∂ t h(t, w)dw + ∫ I ⎛ ⎜ ⎝ 1 - h(t, w) h eq (t, w) ⎞ ⎟ ⎠ ∂ t h eq (t, w)dw = T 3 (t) + T 4 (t).Now, the first term is linked to the entropy productionI D (h|h eq) = 8 ∫ I (1 -w 2)h eq (t, w) ⎛ ⎜ ⎝ ∂ w 4 h(t, w) h eq (t, w) ⎞ ⎟ ⎠ 2 dw ≥ 0,of the Hellinger distance, through the inequality [19] T3 (t) = ∫ I ⎛ ⎜ ⎝ 1 - h eq (t, w) h(t, w) ⎞ ⎟ ⎠ (Q p (h)(t, w) + Q ℓ (h)(t, w))dw = -I D (h|h eq)(t).",
    "(55)Moreover, T 4 (t) can be recast asT 4 (t) = ∫ I (h eq (t, w) - √ h(t, w)h eq (t, w)) ∂ t log h eq (t, w)dw = ∫ I h eq (t, w)∂ t log h eq (t, w)dw -∫ I √ h(t, w)h eq (t, w)∂ t log h eq (t, w)dw,from which we initially deduce, using the previous computations on ∂ t log h eq (t, w) to deal with the first integral and the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality to deal with the second one, thatT 4 (t) ≤ ηe -τ t (1 + ∫ I | log(1 -w)|h eq (t, w)dw + ∫ I | log(1 + w)|h eq (t, w)dw) + ( ∫ I h(t, w)dw) 1 2 =1( ∫ I h eq (t, w) (∂ t log h eq (t, w)) 2 dw)1 2.Recalling then the minimal regularity of the local equilibrium, we fix 1 < q < q from (50) such that h eq ∈ L ∞ (R +, L q (I)), and we apply Hölder's inequality with exponents q and q ′ = q q-1 to control the functions | log(1 -w)|, log 2 (1 -w), | log(1 + w)|, and log 2 (1 + w), which obviously all belong to any L q ′ (I), q ′ ≥ 1.",
    "Simple computations allow to recover the estimateT 4 (t) ≤ η (1 + ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h eq ∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I)) + ∥log 2 (1 + w)∥ 1/2 L q ′ (I) ∥h eq ∥ 1/2 L ∞ (R+,L q (I))) e -τ t, (56)where the value of η has been suitably redefined to include all dependencies on the upper bounding constants."
